The Ministry of Health Wednesday reported 1,494 cases of the coronavirus — the highest ever recorded in a day. Health workers tested 8,839 samples in the last 24 hours, bumping total tests to 58,587. In a statement, Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said there were 41 foreigners among those who tested positive. “Currently, there are 1,313 patients admitted to various health facilities countrywide, while 5,005 are on home-based isolation and care,” Kagwe said. The high infection numbers were reported as President Uhuru Kenyatta directed all counties to maintain isolation facilities and enhance preparedness. The President said more health workers should be trained, PPE provided and virus control measures enforced. “Fifty-seven patients are in the Intensive Care Unit, 25 of whom are on ventilator support and 27 on supplemental oxygen. Another 95 patients are separately on supplementary oxygen of whom 77 are in the general wards while 18 are in the high dependency unit,” Kagwe said. The CS said 586 patients had recovered from the disease, 413 from the home-based care while 173 discharged from hospitals. Some 38,381 patients have recovered. Twelve patients died. The death toll is 1,051. Per county, Nairobi recorded 414 cases followed by Nakuru 188, Mombasa 173, Kiambu 150, Uasin Gishu 107, Turkana 52 and Kilifi 50. Garissa and Taita Taveta recorded 35 cases each, Kajiado Baringo and West Pokot with 31 each, Laikipia and Kisumu 28 each, Murang’a 14, Machakos 13, Nyandarua, Siaya and Meru 12 cases each and Elgeyo Marakwet with 11. Embu and Kericho had 10 cases each, Narok nine, Kitui and Makueni six, Bomet five, Marsabit and Kakamega four, Lamu and Samburu three, Kwale, Kisii and Tana River two, while Nyamira recorded one.